# Omni Android Project Context

Omni is a voice-controlled Android assistant. Users trigger it with a wake word, speak a command, and the agent loop reads the current screen through accessibility APIs, calls an LLM, and executes UI actions until the task is complete.

## Build And Stack

- Build debug APK with `./gradlew assembleDebug`; install with `./gradlew installDebug`; run lint with `./gradlew lint`.
- Single Android app module using Gradle KTS and the version catalog at `gradle/libs.versions.toml`.
- Package is `com.omni.assistant`; minSdk 29, targetSdk 35, compileSdk 35.
- Kotlin-only codebase with Jetpack Compose, Material 3 dark theme, Navigation Compose, OkHttp, Gson, DataStore Preferences, Coroutines, StateFlow, and Accompanist Permissions.
- There is currently no test suite.

## Architecture

- `agent/AgentController.kt` owns the core loop: read screen, call LLM, execute action, repeat.
- `service/OmniAccessibilityService.kt` reads the accessibility node tree and performs gestures, taps, swipes, and typing.
- `service/OmniListenerService.kt` handles wake word detection and speech recognition as a foreground service.
- `llm/LLMClient.kt` handles direct Claude, OpenAI, and OpenRouter calls and keeps the last 10 conversation turns.
- `data/SettingsRepository.kt` stores settings in DataStore with Flow-based APIs.
- `data/AgentState.kt` defines the main sealed state and action models.

## Conventions

- Follow official Kotlin style, pure Compose UI, and no XML layouts.
- Prefer the existing singleton and `StateFlow` patterns before introducing new architecture.
- Use suspend functions and coroutine scopes with `SupervisorJob` for async work.
- Keep screen descriptions capped at 4000 characters, accessibility traversal depth capped at 10, and activity logs capped at 100 entries.
- Keep changes scoped to the package layout: `agent/`, `data/`, `llm/`, `receiver/`, `service/`, and `ui/`.
